{
  "doc_id": "21416",
  "text": "The YAP gene resides within a chromosomal region (11q22) that is amplified in various cancers, and several reports indicate that YAP can function as an oncogene. Indeed, YAP overexpression drives tumor formation in vivo [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] and can transform cells in culture [CITATION_3] , and endogenous YAP is required for tumorigenicity induced by MST1/2 or NF2 loss of function in vivo [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] . Increased YAP abundance is also found in various human cancers, including esophageal [CITATION_7] , gastric [CITATION_8] [CITATION_9] , colon [CITATION_10] , lung [CITATION_11] , and ovarian carcinoma [CITATION_12] , non-small cell lung cancer [CITATION_13] , and hepatocellular carcinoma [CITATION_14] , for which increased YAP abundance is an adverse prognostic marker. However, YAP loss of heterozygosity and reduced protein abundance occur in some cancers, and YAP depletion can promote cell survival [CITATION_15] [CITATION_16] , enhance migration and invasion, and promote tumor growth in immunocompromised mice [CITATION_17] , suggesting that YAP can also act as a tumor suppressor in some contexts.",
